---
description: Cross-engine game development conventions
alwaysApply: true
---

When working on game code or assets:

1. Keep update/render/input loops explicit — avoid hidden per-frame work in getters or property accessors.
2. Name assets consistently (prefix by type: `tex_`, `sfx_`, `ui_`, or follow repo convention).
3. Prefer data-driven tuning (constants, resources, config) over magic numbers in logic.
4. Note playtest observations when changing feel, balance, or difficulty.
5. Profile before optimizing hot paths; measure frame time and allocations.
6. Keep scenes/nodes organized — one responsibility per node when practical.
7. Give immediate player feedback for actions (visual, audio, UI) — silent failures confuse playtesters.
8. Separate simulation logic from rendering and input when practical — aids testing and determinism.
9. Treat save/load, pause, and menu state as first-class systems — regressions here block shipping.
10. Document reproduction steps for gameplay bugs (seed, inputs, scene) before fixing feel issues.
11. Prefer engine-native lifecycle hooks (`_process`, `Update`, `Tick`) over ad-hoc timers for per-frame work.
12. Keep platform and build-target differences behind config or feature flags, not scattered conditionals.
